    "question": "A hedge fund with net capital of GBP500 million has borrowed an additional GBP200 million at 4.5% per annum. The current-year return of the fund is 15%. What would have been the return if the fund had not added any leverage?",
    "options": {
      "A": "10.7%",
      "B": "12.0%",
      "C": "19.2%"
    },
    "answer": "B",
    "userWrongAnswer": "C",
    "explanation": "B is correct.\n\nUsing Equation 2,\n\nrL = Leveraged portfolio return/Cash position = [r × (Vb + Vc ) – (Vb × rb )]/Vc .\nOr, after re-arranging the formula,\nr= \n( Vc×rL )+(Vb×rb)\n\n\n(Vc+Vb)\n .\nSubstituting rL = 0.15, Vb = 200, Vc = 500, rb = 0.045,\nr = (500 × 0.15) + (200 × 0.045)/(200 + 500) = 12%.\n\nSince leverage magnifies return when the borrowing cost is lower than asset returns, the unleveraged asset return must be lower than 15%."
